    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>(Private)</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                <date>16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Aug 5618</date>
            </p>
            <p>Rev and Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I have delayed send<lb/>-ing you the enclosed letter till now<lb/>
                when I have the happiness to trans-<lb/>-mit you an order for two copies of<lb/>
                your Bible—the small edition $2. a copy.<lb/> I think can dispose of at least
                four<lb/> other copies if you have them for sale<lb/> A Christian gentleman—a
                particular<lb/> friend desires one of the two copies and<lb/> the other I wish for
                myself having hither<lb/>-to used my dear friend's <persName>Geo A Dr.</persName>
                copy.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">If you would like me to dispose<lb/> of ½ doz copies I think I can
                without<lb/> trouble.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Since writing you previously<lb/>
                <persName>Dr Wise</persName> has paid a visit here enroute<lb/> for
                    <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>. He spent four days inclu<lb/>-ding
                    <date>Sabbath</date> and <date>Sunday</date>. On the former<lb/> he delivered a
                discourse in German be-<lb/>-fore the Anslu Chesed Kahal and on the<lb/> latter
                    <date>Sunday</date> morning one before ours the<lb/> “Tifereth Israel” in
                English. I heard the<lb/> latter. Its subject was “Judaism its princi-<lb/>-ples”
                His text was taken from Isaiah</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>He defined Judaism under four heads.</p>
            <p>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> A belief in One God</p>
            <p>2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> Man was created in the image of God</p>
            <p>3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> Since man was created in the image of God<lb/> he should
                endeavor to walk in his ways &amp; imi-<lb/>tate his perfection.</p>
            <p>4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> The Coming Messiah. The <sic>fulfilment</sic> of the<lb/>
                covenant would be the messianic period.<lb/> He denied a personal messiah said the
                fulfill<lb/>-ment of the covenant would be the general<lb/> perfection of
                mankind—nay the complete re-<lb/>generation of man—when all the world would<lb/>
                embrace Judaism believe in but One God<lb/> and have but one Religion. In a
                word<lb/> that the Jews were to be the messiahs as they<lb/> were <del>the</del> a
                nation of priests they would in<lb/> the fullness of time bring all mankind to<lb/>
                their belief and thus redeem the world<lb/> &amp;c &amp;c in the same train.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Both the congregations here being orthodox<lb/>
                <del>here</del> took many exceptions as you may sup<lb/>-pose to his remarks—nay I
                think it safe<lb/> to say—the mass differed widely with<lb/> him—but that would not
                signify much<lb/> perhaps, <hi rend="underline">considering</hi> the <hi
                    rend="underline">components</hi> of the <hi rend="underline">mass</hi><lb/>
                However I heard a number of highly intelli<lb/>-gent Jews express their dissent in
                terms</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>not at all complimentary to the Rev Dr.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">He made little or no impression other<lb/> than by his presence
                securing additional<lb/>
                <sic>subscrition</sic> to the Israelite and collecting<lb/> from delinquents—in both
                of which I learn<lb/> he was quite successful. You know the<lb/> object of his visit
                to <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>—from there<lb/> he goes to <placeName>N.
                    Y.</placeName> to attend the <date>August</date> meeting<lb/> of the Con G.
                Lodge JOBB.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am devoting much of<lb/> my leisure to the study of our history
                and religion<lb/> limited indeed are the sources from whence<lb/> I can derive the
                information my mind seeks<lb/> my thirst craves. I realize fully the value<lb/> of
                your opening editorial Vol V No 1. “De-<lb/>mand for Education.” the Mishna
                Talmud<lb/> and Posekin<add>?</add> are indeed sealed books to<lb/> me. I would
                study the Chaldaic tongue<lb/> but can find no teacher and being but an
                in<lb/>different Hebrew Scholar I make little<lb/> progress. However I do not
                despair. The Pen<lb/>-tatuech and Prophets are the source of<lb/> unalloyed
                enjoyment though I often very<lb/> often am at a loss and pray for a
                commenta<lb/>-tor. I trust you will be able to dis-<lb/>-cuss the question
                propounded in my letter<lb/> of the <date>9<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> in your
                    <date>October</date> number I shall</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>forward to it with anxiety.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The recent triumph of Judaism in <placeName>England</placeName><lb/>
                is looked upon by <persName>Dr Wise</persName> as another evidence<lb/> of the
                emancipation of <placeName>Israel</placeName> and their growing<lb/> importance. He
                says “this is another evidence<lb/> of the growing intelligence of mankind—our<lb/>
                people are being redeemed from the Heralldom<add>?</add><lb/> of ages and in due
                time willcome to be<lb/> regarded as the God of <placeName>Israel</placeName>
                intended they<lb/> should be. They will be a <hi rend="underline">nation of
                    priests</hi> in<lb/> truth and will lead the world up to God<lb/> through the
                faith of <persName>Abraham</persName> “&amp;c</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Pardon me for intruding at<lb/> such length upon your valuable time
                with <del>by</del><lb/> my deultory correspondence and<lb/> with renewed wishes of
                good health<lb/> believe me most truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">B F. Peixotto</persName>
            </p>
            <p>My dear wife &amp; all your friends here<lb/> desire their affectionate regards.</p>
            <p>I enclose a brief paragraph for publi-<lb/>cation (if not too late) in
                    <date>Sept</date> No.</p>
        </body>
